"""
christ layer: Joshua 21–23.
Ch 21 (45 v): Levitical cities — vv 1-44 missing (v45 already exists).
Ch 22 (34 v): Eastern tribes return; witness-altar controversy resolved.
Ch 23 (16 v): Joshua's farewell — divine faithfulness, covenant warning.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>A type: the heads of the Levitical fathers&rsquo; houses came to Eleazar the priest and to Joshua and to the heads of the fathers&rsquo; houses of the tribes of Israel at Shiloh in Canaan and spoke to them. The Levites come last — after all twelve tribes have received their allotments — to claim the cities YHWH promised through Moses (Num 35:1-8). The Levitical claim is not territorial conquest but inherited entitlement, received through the covenant promise. Hebrews 7:11-14 argues that the Levitical priesthood is insufficient and gives way to the Melchizedekian order in Christ — yet the principle of priestly provision by divine command is fulfilled in Christ&rsquo;s priestly provision for his people, distributed not through territorial cities but through his own indwelling presence.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A type: the command YHWH gave through Moses — that we be given cities to dwell in, with pasturelands for our livestock. The appeal to Moses&rsquo;s command at Shiloh (the central sanctuary) frames the Levitical claim as a matter of covenant right, not tribal negotiation. The priestly tribe does not take; it receives what YHWH commanded the other tribes to give. In the NT, the priesthood of all believers (1 Pet 2:9) receives its provision through Christ&rsquo;s own body: &ldquo;he who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all, how will he not also with him graciously give us all things?&rdquo; (Rom 8:32). The Levitical receiving-from-others becomes the model of the church receiving all things through Christ.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A type: by YHWH&rsquo;s command the Israelites gave the Levites these cities and their pasturelands from their own inheritances. The act of the twelve tribes giving from their own portions to support the priestly tribe is the covenant structure of mutual provision: the Levites serve the whole nation, and the whole nation provides for the Levites. Paul applies this principle to gospel ministry: &ldquo;Let the one who is taught the word share all good things with the one who teaches&rdquo; (Gal 6:6). The Levitical support principle — those who minister at the altar live from the altar (1 Cor 9:13-14) — is the type of the church&rsquo;s provision for those who proclaim the gospel.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A type: the lot fell for the Kohathites — the clan of Aaron the priest received thirteen cities from Judah, Simeon, and Benjamin. The Aaronite Kohathites, the high-priestly clan, receive cities in Judah&rsquo;s territory — the tribe from which David and the Messiah will come. The high priesthood and the royal tribe are geographically neighbors; Jerusalem itself (later Judah&rsquo;s royal city) is adjacent to the priestly cities. In Christ, the royal-priestly union is personalized: he holds both offices in one person (Heb 7:1-3: after the order of Melchizedek, &ldquo;king of righteousness&rdquo; and &ldquo;king of peace&rdquo;).</p>",
    "5": "<p>A type: the rest of the Kohathites received ten cities from the tribe of Ephraim, Dan, and the half-tribe of Manasseh. The non-Aaronite Kohathites carry the holy furniture of the tabernacle (Num 4:4-20) — the ark, the table of showbread, the menorah, the altars — all covered and carried on poles through the wilderness. The bearers of the sacred objects of God&rsquo;s dwelling receive cities in the central and northern tribes, positioned throughout the land as custodians of the tabernacle tradition. In the new covenant, the bearers of the sacred mystery — the church — carry the gospel (&ldquo;treasure in jars of clay,&rdquo; 2 Cor 4:7) throughout the nations as the Kohathites carried the sacred furnishings throughout the land.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A type: the Gershonites received thirteen cities from the tribes of Issachar, Asher, Naphtali, and the half-tribe of Manasseh in Bashan. The Gershonites carried the fabrics and coverings of the tabernacle (Num 4:24-26) — the curtains, veils, and coverings that formed the visible structure of YHWH&rsquo;s dwelling. Their cities in the northern tribes (Issachar, Asher, Naphtali) placed the tabernacle-covering tradition in the region that will become &ldquo;Galilee of the Gentiles&rdquo; (Isa 9:1-2; Matt 4:15-16) — the area where Jesus conducted most of his ministry. The fabric-bearers&rsquo; inheritance was in the territory where the Word became flesh and tabernacled among us (John 1:14).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A type: the Merarites received twelve cities from the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and Zebulun. The Merarites carried the structural elements of the tabernacle — the frames, bars, pillars, and bases (Num 4:31-33). Their inheritance includes the Transjordanian tribes (Reuben and Gad) who are separated from the main body of Israel by the Jordan. The Merarites&rsquo; priestly presence in the separated territories is the type of the church&rsquo;s ministry in the margins: the priestly community is sent not only to the central, accessible tribes but to those on the far side of the boundary. Acts 1:8 — &ldquo;to the ends of the earth&rdquo; — is the NT expansion of the Merarite model.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A type: the Israelites assigned these cities with their pasturelands to the Levites by lot, as YHWH had commanded through Moses. The lot-assignment confirms the divine character of the Levitical distribution: even the priestly city allocations are determined by YHWH&rsquo;s direction, not tribal preference. The pastoral provision — cities and pasturelands (<em>migrash</em>) — ensures that the priests can both minister in the sanctuary and sustain their households. Christ&rsquo;s provision for his servants includes both the ministry of his word and the material sustenance needed to carry it out (Matt 10:9-10: workers deserve their wage; Luke 10:7).</p>",
    "9": "<p>A type: the cities assigned from the tribes of Judah and Simeon — the firstfruits of the priestly city allocation. Judah&rsquo;s role as host to the Aaronite priestly cities anticipates Judah&rsquo;s hosting of Jerusalem — the city of the temple, the city of David, the city of Christ&rsquo;s death and resurrection. The priestly cities embedded in Judah&rsquo;s territory lay the groundwork for the Jerusalem sanctuary tradition that culminates in the temple of Christ&rsquo;s body (John 2:19-21).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A type: the cities going to the Aaronite Kohathites (the first lot among the Levites). The &ldquo;first lot&rdquo; going to the Aaronites is the covenant priority structure: the Aaronite high priesthood takes precedence in the Levitical distribution. Hebrews 5:4 notes that &ldquo;no one takes this honor for himself, but only when called by God, just as Aaron was&rdquo; — the Aaronite priority in the lot reflects the divine call that precedes priestly service. Christ was called by the divine voice at his baptism (Matt 3:17: &ldquo;This is my beloved Son&rdquo;) and transfiguration (Matt 17:5) — his high priesthood rests on divine appointment, not human selection.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A type: Kiriath-arba (the city of Arba, the father of Anak) — that is, Hebron — in the hill country of Judah, with its surrounding pasturelands. Hebron is given to the Levites as one of their cities — the same city just given to Caleb as his personal inheritance (ch. 14). The resolution is v12: the fields and villages go to Caleb; the city itself (within its walls) goes to the Levites. The co-inhabitation of Hebron by Caleb (the faithful warrior) and the Levitical priests (the covenant ministers) models the complementary vocations of warrior-faith and priestly service that are united in Christ&rsquo;s person as both priest and king.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A type: the fields of the city and its villages they gave to Caleb son of Jephunneh as his possession. The distinction between the city proper (given to the Levites) and the fields/villages (given to Caleb) preserves both inheritances within the same territory. The tension is resolved not by exclusion but by complementary allocation. In Christ, the royal and priestly functions are not competitive but complementary: &ldquo;He is the atoning sacrifice for our sins&rdquo; (priestly, 1 John 2:2) and &ldquo;the ruler of the kings of the earth&rdquo; (royal, Rev 1:5) — both offices fully inhabited, neither diminishing the other.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A type: Hebron is a city of refuge for the manslayer. The Levitical cities include six cities of refuge (Josh 20) — Hebron, Shechem, Kedesh, Bezer, Ramoth, and Golan — where anyone who killed unintentionally could flee from the blood-avenger. Hebrews 6:18: &ldquo;we who have fled for refuge might have strong encouragement to hold fast to the hope set before us&rdquo; — the six cities of refuge are the type of Christ as the one asylum where those guilty before the divine law may find safety. The city of refuge was Levitical: the priestly city, not the military city, is the place of life-saving asylum.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A type: Libnah with its pasturelands, Jattir with its pasturelands — additional Aaronite cities in Judah. The distribution of the priestly cities throughout Judah ensures that priestly presence is not concentrated only at the central sanctuary but dispersed through the territory. The church as &ldquo;a royal priesthood&rdquo; (1 Pet 2:9) is similarly dispersed: not gathered in one sacred location but scattered through every city, town, and village, carrying priestly mediation through prayer, proclamation, and embodied witness.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A type: Eshtemoa with its pasturelands, Holon with its pasturelands — Aaronite cities continuing. The pastoral dispersal of the Levitical cities throughout Judah&rsquo;s territory models the church&rsquo;s dispersal through the Roman Empire (Acts 8:1-4: the persecution scattering the Jerusalem church throughout Judea and Samaria — &ldquo;those who were scattered went about preaching the word&rdquo;). What appears to be forced dispersal becomes priestly dispersal: the scattered community carries its priestly function wherever it goes.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A type: Ain with its pasturelands, Juttah with its pasturelands, Beth-shemesh with its pasturelands — nine cities total from the two tribes of Judah and Simeon. Beth-shemesh (&ldquo;house of the sun&rdquo;) is where the ark was returned from Philistine captivity (1 Sam 6:13-15) — a Levitical city in Judah that received the ark&rsquo;s return. The city named for the sun hosts the return of YHWH&rsquo;s presence-object: a type of Christ as the Sun of Righteousness (Mal 4:2) whose priestly city is wherever his presence returns to his people.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A type: four cities from the tribe of Benjamin — Gibeon with its pasturelands, Geba with its pasturelands. Gibeon is the great high place where Solomon will offer a thousand burnt offerings, and where YHWH will appear to him in a dream and grant him wisdom (1 Kings 3:4-5). The Levitical city of Gibeon becomes the site of the definitive royal theophany that shapes Solomon&rsquo;s reign. The priestly city mediates the divine encounter that orients the king — the type of the Holy Spirit&rsquo;s anointing of Christ at his baptism (Matt 3:16-17: the Spirit descended as the priestly anointing of the royal Son).</p>",
    "18": "<p>A type: Anathoth with its pasturelands and Almon with its pasturelands — four cities of Benjamin for the Aaronites. Anathoth is the priestly city from which Jeremiah came (Jer 1:1: &ldquo;the words of Jeremiah son of Hilkiah, one of the priests at Anathoth in Benjamin&rdquo;). The Levitical priestly city of Anathoth produces the weeping prophet who becomes the most Christological figure in the OT: the suffering righteous one rejected by his own people (Jer 11:19: &ldquo;like a gentle lamb led to the slaughter&rdquo;; cf. Isa 53:7). Christ comes from a Levitical-Aaronite city&rsquo;s prophetic tradition through Jeremiah.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A type: all the cities of the Aaronites — thirteen cities in all with their pasturelands. The summary of the Aaronite priestly cities — thirteen in number, spanning Judah, Simeon, and Benjamin — captures the high-priestly provision across the southern kingdom&rsquo;s territory. The number thirteen is one more than twelve — the extra city beyond the tribal count, as Christ is the high priest who stands beyond and above the Levitical order (Heb 7:24: &ldquo;he holds his priesthood permanently, because he continues forever&rdquo;).</p>",
    "20": "<p>A type: the remaining Kohathite Levites received cities from the tribe of Ephraim. Ephraim is the tribe of Joshua himself — the military leader whose name is embedded in the priestly city-allotments. Joshua the military leader and Eleazar the high priest together distributed the inheritance (14:1); now their own tribal territories host the Levitical cities. The military-priestly partnership throughout the book of Joshua foreshadows the single Person who fulfills both roles: Christ as both the captain who fights for his people (Heb 2:10: &ldquo;pioneer of their salvation&rdquo;) and the high priest who intercedes for them (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "21": "<p>A type: Shechem with its pasturelands in the hill country of Ephraim — a city of refuge — and Gezer with its pasturelands. Shechem is the covenant city where Abraham first built an altar (Gen 12:6-7), where Jacob purchased land (Gen 33:18-20), where the bones of Joseph will be buried (Josh 24:32), and where the Ebal covenant ceremony was held (Josh 8:30-35). The great covenant-gathering city is a city of refuge — the place of covenant renewal is also the place of asylum. Jesus&rsquo;s encounter with the Samaritan woman at Jacob&rsquo;s well in Sychar/Shechem (John 4:5-42) is the NT covenant-renewal at the type&rsquo;s location: the true city of refuge meeting the woman fleeing her own failures.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A type: Kibzaim with its pasturelands and Beth-horon with its pasturelands — two more cities for the Kohathites in Ephraim. Beth-horon (upper and lower) is the strategic pass where Joshua&rsquo;s famous long day occurred (Josh 10:10-14: YHWH threw down great hailstones on the Amorites) — the pass where the most explicit divine intervention in the conquest happened. The Levitical city at Beth-horon is the priestly presence at the site of the most dramatic divine warrior-act: YHWH&rsquo;s throwing of hailstones is the cosmic-warrior act that mirrors the final divine warrior-act of Revelation 16:21 (&ldquo;great hailstones, each weighing about a hundred pounds, fell from heaven&rdquo;).</p>",
    "23": "<p>A type: four cities from the tribe of Dan — Eltekeh and Gibbethon with their pasturelands. Dan&rsquo;s territory is the coastal lowland near Philistia — the most contested boundary of the conquest. The Levitical presence in Dan&rsquo;s territory was strategic: the tribe nearest the Philistines needed the priestly cities as covenantal anchors. Dan will eventually migrate north (Judg 18) and set up an idolatrous shrine — the failure of the Danite covenant identity. The Levitical cities in Dan represent the divine provision of priestly presence that was offered but ultimately not maintained, a type of the grace that can be squandered through covenant unfaithfulness.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A type: Aijalon with its pasturelands and Gath-rimmon with its pasturelands — additional Danite-Kohathite cities. Aijalon is the valley of the long day (Josh 10:12: &ldquo;moon, stand still over the Valley of Aijalon&rdquo;) — the site of the cosmic stoppage where YHWH fought for Israel. The Levitical city in the valley of the long day connects priestly ministry with the most spectacular demonstration of YHWH&rsquo;s cosmic sovereignty over creation in service of his covenant people. Second Peter 3:8 (&ldquo;with the Lord one day is as a thousand years, and a thousand years as one day&rdquo;) is the NT meditation on the same divine sovereignty over time that the long day at Aijalon embodied.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A type: two cities from the half-tribe of Manasseh — Taanach and Gath-rimmon. Taanach is the site of Deborah&rsquo;s battle against Sisera (Judg 5:19: &ldquo;the kings came and fought; at Taanach, by the waters of Megiddo, they got no spoils of silver&rdquo;) — the Levitical city in the Jezreel Valley becomes the setting for Israel&rsquo;s future deliverances through the judges. The priestly cities scattered through Israel function as covenant anchors that make possible the periodic redemptions of the judges period: the Levitical presence in Taanach represents the sustained covenant witness that grounds each subsequent act of divine deliverance.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A type: ten cities in all with their pasturelands for the rest of the Kohathite clans. The ten non-Aaronite Kohathite cities (vv. 20-26) span four tribes — Ephraim, Dan, half-Manasseh — positioning the bearers of the ark and tabernacle furnishings throughout the central region of the land. The Kohathites at the center of the Levitical structure hold the most sacred objects of divine presence: the ark (type of Christ as the mercy seat, Rom 3:25: &ldquo;God put forward as a propitiation by his blood&rdquo;) and the table of showbread (type of Christ as the bread of life, John 6:35). Their ten cities are the priestly presence sustaining the land&rsquo;s covenant life.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A type: the Gershonites received two cities — Golan in Bashan (a city of refuge) and Be-eshterah from the half-tribe of Manasseh. Golan in Bashan is the northernmost city of refuge — the asylum point at the far end of the land, in the territory of the defeated giant-king Og. The city of refuge at the edge of the conquered enemy&rsquo;s domain is the type of Christ&rsquo;s reach: the furthest, most seemingly unreachable place still has a city of asylum for those who flee to him. Hebrews 7:25: &ldquo;he is able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him.&rdquo;</p>",
    "28": "<p>A type: from the tribe of Issachar — Kishion with its pasturelands and Daberath with its pasturelands. Daberath is the town at the foot of Mount Tabor, where Deborah and Barak assembled before the battle against Sisera (Judg 4:6, 14). Mount Tabor is the probable location of the Transfiguration (Matt 17:1-8; Mark 9:2-8; Luke 9:28-36 — the &ldquo;high mountain apart&rdquo;). The Levitical town at the foot of the mountain of divine glory connects the priestly-city tradition directly to the site of Christ&rsquo;s eschatological self-revelation in the Synoptics.</p>",
    "29": "<p>A type: Jarmuth with its pasturelands and En-gannim with its pasturelands from Issachar. En-gannim (&ldquo;spring of the gardens&rdquo;) may be the same Jenin area that appears in the NT in the vicinity of the ten lepers&rsquo; healing (Luke 17:11-19: &ldquo;on the way to Jerusalem he was passing along between Samaria and Galilee,&rdquo; where one leper returned to give thanks). The Levitical spring-town in Issachar connects to the region of Jesus&rsquo;s healing ministry, and the grateful Samaritan leper who returned — the foreigner who gave thanks — is the type of the Caleb-pattern: the outsider who comes back in faith and receives blessing.</p>",
    "30": "<p>A type: from the tribe of Asher — Mishal with its pasturelands and Abdon with its pasturelands. Asher&rsquo;s territory stretches along the Phoenician coast — the northern boundary of the land with access to Tyre and Sidon. The Levitical cities in Asher place priestly presence at the interface with the great Phoenician city-states, the most culturally sophisticated neighbors of Israel. Jesus&rsquo;s journey to the region of Tyre and Sidon (Mark 7:24-31) extends the covenant blessing beyond these Asherite boundary cities to the Gentile woman who worships him — the priestly-city border is expanded by Christ to encompass those beyond Israel&rsquo;s geographical limits.</p>",
    "31": "<p>A type: Helkath with its pasturelands and Rehob with its pasturelands from Asher — four cities. Rehob is the northern boundary point of the Promised Land (Num 13:21: the spies went &ldquo;from the wilderness of Zin to Rehob&rdquo;) — the far northern limit reached in the first reconnaissance. The Levitical city at the land&rsquo;s northern boundary marker is the type of the church&rsquo;s presence at the frontier: Acts 1:8&rsquo;s &ldquo;ends of the earth&rdquo; is the NT expansion of the frontier-city principle — the priestly community is placed even at the furthest boundary of the known world.</p>",
    "32": "<p>A type: from the tribe of Naphtali — Kedesh in Galilee (a city of refuge) with its pasturelands, Hammoth-dor with its pasturelands, Kartan with its pasturelands — three cities. Kedesh in Galilee is the city of refuge in the far north — the northernmost asylum city in Israel. Matthew 4:15-16 (quoting Isa 9:1-2): &ldquo;the land of Zebulun and the land of Naphtali... Galilee of the Gentiles — the people dwelling in darkness have seen a great light.&rdquo; The northernmost city of refuge (Kedesh-naphtali) is in the territory where Jesus brought the light of the gospel — the asylum-city of Joshua&rsquo;s Galilee becomes the territory of Christ&rsquo;s liberating ministry.</p>",
    "33": "<p>A type: all the cities of the Gershonites — thirteen cities with their pasturelands. The Gershonite total — thirteen cities, the same number as the Aaronites — ensures that the fabric-carriers of the tabernacle have the same scope of priestly presence as the high-priestly clan. In the body of Christ, every member&rsquo;s function is necessary: &ldquo;the body does not consist of one member but of many&rdquo; (1 Cor 12:14). The Gershonite fabric-carriers have the same city-count as the Aaronite altar-ministers — different functions, equal provision, equal dispersal through the land.</p>",
    "34": "<p>A type: to the rest of the Levites — the Merarites — from the tribe of Zebulun: Jokneam with its pasturelands and Kartah with its pasturelands. Jokneam is the city near Mount Carmel, the site of Elijah&rsquo;s confrontation with the prophets of Baal (1 Kings 18:19-40). The Levitical city at Carmel&rsquo;s base positions priestly presence at what will become the decisive site of Israel&rsquo;s Baal-rejection. The Carmel theophany — fire from heaven consuming the sacrifice — is the type of Pentecost (Acts 2:3: &ldquo;tongues of fire... distributed and resting on each one of them&rdquo;), where the Spirit&rsquo;s fire confirms the true sacrifice (Christ) over against every idol.</p>",
    "35": "<p>A type: Dimnah with its pasturelands and Nahalal with its pasturelands from Zebulun — four cities total. The Zebulunite Merarite cities in the lower Galilee region encompass the area of Jesus&rsquo;s hometown district (Nazareth is in the hills of lower Galilee, in Zebulun&rsquo;s territory — Matt 2:23: &ldquo;he shall be called a Nazarene&rdquo;). The structural-element-bearers of the tabernacle have their cities in the tribe that hosts the Word made flesh — the framework-bearers of YHWH&rsquo;s dwelling place are located in the tribal territory of Christ&rsquo;s human home.</p>",
    "36": "<p>A type: from the tribe of Reuben — Bezer with its pasturelands and Jahzah with its pasturelands. Bezer is the city of refuge for the eastern Transjordanian territory — the Reubenite asylum city. The city of refuge in Reuben&rsquo;s territory is in the vicinity of the battle at Jahzah where Sihon was defeated (Num 21:23; Deut 2:32) — the site of the anti-kingdom&rsquo;s defeat hosts the city of refuge. Christ&rsquo;s death at the site of the greatest spiritual conflict becomes the source of asylum: the cross, the site of ultimate conflict, is where the refuge-city is founded for all who flee to him.</p>",
    "37": "<p>A type: Kedemoth with its pasturelands and Mephaath with its pasturelands from Reuben — four cities. Kedemoth is the wilderness from which Moses sent messengers to Sihon offering peace (Deut 2:26). The Levitical city at the peace-offer site is the priestly counterpart to the military mission: the priests inhabit the place from which peace was offered. In Christ, the gospel is the offer of peace from the one place where peace is possible: &ldquo;In Christ God was reconciling the world to himself... and entrusting to us the message of reconciliation&rdquo; (2 Cor 5:19). The Merarite priests at Kedemoth are the type of the ministers of reconciliation.</p>",
    "38": "<p>A type: from the tribe of Gad — Ramoth in Gilead (a city of refuge) with its pasturelands and Mahanaim with its pasturelands. Ramoth in Gilead is one of the six cities of refuge and also the site of two major battles: (1) Ahab is mortally wounded at Ramoth-gilead (1 Kings 22:34-36); (2) Jehu is anointed king there by Elisha&rsquo;s prophetic messenger (2 Kings 9:1-6). The city of refuge becomes the site of royal anointing and judgment. Christ as the anointed king (the Messiah, the Christ — the anointed one) is crowned through the judgment-event of the cross: anointed king by the very act that wounds him mortally (Phil 2:8-9: &ldquo;obedient to the point of death... therefore God has highly exalted him&rdquo;).</p>",
    "39": "<p>A type: Heshbon with its pasturelands and Jazer with its pasturelands from Gad — four cities. Heshbon was Sihon&rsquo;s capital — the anti-kingdom&rsquo;s administrative center — now a Levitical city. The priests inhabit the former enemy capital, transforming the seat of resistance into a place of covenant service. Second Corinthians 10:4-5: &ldquo;we destroy arguments and every lofty opinion raised against the knowledge of God, and take every thought captive to obey Christ&rdquo; — the Levitical occupation of Heshbon is the type of Christ&rsquo;s priestly presence transforming former strongholds of the enemy into centers of covenant worship.</p>",
    "40": "<p>A type: all the cities allotted to the Merarites — twelve cities in total. The Merarite twelve matches the twelve tribes — one city per tribe in the structural-bearing clan&rsquo;s allotment, ensuring that the framework of YHWH&rsquo;s dwelling is present throughout the entire covenant community. In the new covenant, the Holy Spirit indwells every believer (1 Cor 3:16: &ldquo;you are God&rsquo;s temple and God&rsquo;s Spirit dwells in you&rdquo;) — the Merarite framework-presence, distributed one city per tribe, is the type of the Spirit&rsquo;s distributed presence in every member of the new covenant assembly.</p>",
    "41": "<p>A type: the total — forty-eight cities with their pasturelands for the Levites within the possession of the people of Israel. The number forty-eight is the complete Levitical city count: four Levitical clans (Aaronite Kohathites 13 + non-Aaronite Kohathites 10 + Gershonites 13 + Merarites 12 = 48). Forty-eight cities distributed through all twelve tribes — four per tribe — ensures no tribal territory is without a priestly city. The mathematical completeness of the Levitical city distribution (every tribe, four cities each) is the type of the Spirit&rsquo;s comprehensive provision: no member of the body of Christ is without access to the priestly ministry of the word and intercession (Heb 4:16: &ldquo;let us then with confidence draw near to the throne of grace&rdquo;).</p>",
    "42": "<p>A type: each of these cities had its pasturelands surrounding it — so for all these cities. The <em>migrash</em> (pastureland) provision is the Levites&rsquo; equivalent of the tribal &ldquo;fields and villages&rdquo; given to Caleb: the priestly city includes not only the urban center but the surrounding agricultural land to sustain the priestly household. The complete provision — city and pastureland — is the type of Christ&rsquo;s complete provision: not only access to his priestly presence (the city) but the daily sustenance to live in it (the pastureland). Matthew 6:31-33: &ldquo;do not be anxious... your heavenly Father knows you need all these things. Seek first the kingdom and his righteousness, and all these things will be added to you.&rdquo;</p>",
    "43": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Thus YHWH gave to Israel all the land that he swore to give to their fathers. And they took possession of it and settled there.&rdquo; This verse is the first of the book&rsquo;s two great summary-fulfillment statements (the second is v45). The land-gift is stated in the same terms as the patriarchal promise (Gen 12:7; 13:15; 15:18-21; 17:8; 26:3; 28:13) — what was sworn is now given. Galatians 3:16-18: &ldquo;the promises were made to Abraham and to his offspring... God gave it to Abraham by a promise&rdquo; — the inheritance-by-promise is not the Sinaitic law but the covenant with Abraham, fulfilled in Christ who is the true offspring (Gal 3:16: &ldquo;not &lsquo;and to offsprings,&rsquo; as referring to many, but as to one, &lsquo;and to your offspring,&rsquo; who is Christ&rdquo;). The land-fulfillment of Joshua 21:43 is the type; the inheritance-fulfillment in Christ is the antitype.</p>",
    "44": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;And YHWH gave them rest on every side just as he had sworn to their fathers. Not one of all their enemies withstood them, for YHWH gave all their enemies into their hands.&rdquo; The rest-gift on every side is the fulfillment of the holy-war promise (Deut 3:20: &ldquo;until YHWH gives rest to your brothers, as he has given rest to you&rdquo;; Josh 1:13, 15). Hebrews 4:9-10: &ldquo;there remains a Sabbath rest for the people of God, for whoever has entered God&rsquo;s rest has also rested from his works as God did from his.&rdquo; The rest at Canaan&rsquo;s conquest is a real but provisional fulfillment: the complete rest, from which no enemy can disturb, is the eschatological Sabbath-rest that Christ gives (Matt 11:28-29: &ldquo;come to me... and I will give you rest... you will find rest for your souls&rdquo;).</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>A type: Joshua called the Reubenites, Gadites, and half-tribe of Manasseh — the completion of the Transjordanian tribes&rsquo; service commitment. They had promised to help the western tribes conquer Canaan before receiving their own inheritance (Josh 1:12-15); now Joshua formally releases them. The dismissal pattern — faithful service completed, formal release given, return to inheritance — is the type of the servant&rsquo;s completion of commissioned work. Christ&rsquo;s words at the cross &ldquo;It is finished&rdquo; (<em>tetelestai</em>, John 19:30) are the ultimate completion announcement: the service-commitment to the Father&rsquo;s mission accomplished, the return to glory (John 17:4-5) secured.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A direct revelation (through Joshua&rsquo;s words): &ldquo;You have kept all that Moses the servant of YHWH commanded you and have obeyed my voice in all that I have commanded you.&rdquo; The commendation of the eastern tribes&rsquo; faithful service is the form of the covenant verdict: &ldquo;well done, good and faithful servant&rdquo; (Matt 25:21). Joshua&rsquo;s words here anticipate Christ&rsquo;s final judgment-commendation — the covenant leader&rsquo;s verdict on the covenant community&rsquo;s faithfulness. The Transjordanian tribes receive the commendation before crossing to their inheritance, as believers will receive the commendation at the judgment before entering the final inheritance.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A type: &ldquo;You have not forsaken your brothers these many days, down to this day, but have been careful to keep the charge of YHWH your God.&rdquo; The faithfulness through the long campaign — the &ldquo;many days&rdquo; of the entire conquest — is the evidence Joshua cites. Covenantal faithfulness is demonstrated through duration, not merely intensity: not the dramatic initial commitment but the sustained presence through the years of conflict. Hebrews 3:14: &ldquo;we have come to share in Christ, if indeed we hold our original confidence firm to the end.&rdquo; The holding firm through the many days is the form of the covenant faithfulness that Joshua commends.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A direct revelation (through Joshua): &ldquo;And now YHWH your God has given rest to your brothers, as he promised them. Therefore turn and go to your tents in the land where your possession lies, which Moses the servant of YHWH gave you beyond the Jordan.&rdquo; The dismissal to the inheritance is the completion of service leading to Sabbath: work done, rest entered. The rest-gift given to all Israel now allows the service-workers to rest in their own inheritance. Philippians 4:7: &ldquo;the peace of God, which surpasses all understanding, will guard your hearts and minds in Christ Jesus&rdquo; — the peace after faithful service is YHWH&rsquo;s gift, not the warrior&rsquo;s achievement.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A direct revelation (Joshua&rsquo;s charge): &ldquo;Only be very careful to observe the commandment and the law that Moses the servant of YHWH commanded you, to love YHWH your God, and to walk in all his ways and to keep his commandments and to cling to him and to serve him with all your heart and with all your soul.&rdquo; This verse contains the Shema applied to covenant life in the land: the full-devotion formula that Jesus names as the greatest commandment (Matt 22:37-38: &ldquo;Love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind — this is the great and first commandment&rdquo;). Joshua&rsquo;s charge at the tribal dismissal is a rehearsal of the Shema; Jesus&rsquo;s summary of the law is its fulfillment and distillation.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A type: Joshua blessed them and sent them away, and they went to their tents. The blessing before departure — the covenant leader&rsquo;s benediction that releases the community to their inheritance — is the priestly blessing function. Numbers 6:24-26: &ldquo;YHWH bless you and keep you; YHWH make his face shine on you and be gracious to you&rdquo; — the Aaronite blessing given through the priests. Christ&rsquo;s ascension blessing over his disciples (Luke 24:50-51: &ldquo;lifting up his hands he blessed them. While he blessed them, he parted from them and was carried up into heaven&rdquo;) is the definitive priestly blessing at the moment of departure — the ascending leader&rsquo;s benediction releasing his people to their mission.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A type: to the half-tribe of Manasseh Moses had given a portion in Bashan, and to the other half Joshua had given a portion among their brothers west of the Jordan. The split inheritance of Manasseh — half east, half west of the Jordan — creates a tribe whose unity spans both sides of the covenant boundary. The divided-but-united Manasseh is the type of the church&rsquo;s unity across cultural boundaries: neither the Transjordanian nor the Cisjordanian half is the &ldquo;real&rdquo; Manasseh — both halves together constitute the tribe. Ephesians 2:14: &ldquo;he himself is our peace, who has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility.&rdquo;</p>",
    "8": "<p>A type: Joshua blessed the eastern tribes and sent them home with great wealth — livestock, silver, gold, bronze, iron, and a great quantity of clothing. The blessing includes sharing the plunder of the conquest — the eastern tribes, though they received their inheritance east of the Jordan, share in the wealth of the western campaign. Second Corinthians 8:9: &ldquo;though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor, so that you by his poverty might become rich&rdquo; — the pattern of wealth-sharing through covenant service is the type of Christ&rsquo;s kenosis producing abundance for his people. The eastern tribes go home enriched by the western conquest they helped accomplish.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A type: the Reubenites and Gadites and the half-tribe of Manasseh left the people of Israel at Shiloh and went to the land of Gilead. Shiloh, the central sanctuary site, is the last shared covenant-space before the separation. The departure from Shiloh — the place of YHWH&rsquo;s tabernacle — marks the transition from shared worship-space to separated territorial existence. The theology of separation from the visible sanctuary will become urgent in the altar-controversy (vv. 10-34): can YHWH&rsquo;s presence be claimed apart from the official sanctuary? John 4:21-24 resolves this definitively: neither on this mountain nor in Jerusalem — the true worshipers worship in spirit and truth, wherever they are.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A type: at the Jordan, in the land of Canaan, the Reubenites and Gadites and half-tribe of Manasseh built there an altar — a large and impressive altar. The altar at the Jordan is not a sacrifice-altar but a witness-monument — though the western tribes misunderstand it as apostasy and prepare for civil war. The misunderstanding of an act of covenant commitment as an act of rebellion is the hermeneutical crisis that the chapter resolves. The cross is the ultimate hermeneutical crisis: what appeared to be God&rsquo;s judgment and defeat of the righteous one was YHWH&rsquo;s supreme act of covenant faithfulness. The Jordan altar is &ldquo;impressive&rdquo; (<em>gadol lemar'eh</em>); the cross is an instrument of execution — both look like the wrong thing until properly interpreted.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A type: the people of Israel heard, &ldquo;Behold, the people of Reuben and the people of Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh have built the altar at the frontier of the land of Canaan, at the Jordan.&rdquo; The report reaches the whole community as a shock — an altar outside the approved sanctuary location seemed to violate the deuteronomic command of centralized worship (Deut 12:5-14). The community&rsquo;s immediate alarm reflects the same principle as Galatians 1:6-9: a different gospel is no gospel at all, and the alarm at theological deviation is itself a sign of covenantal seriousness. The western tribes&rsquo; alarm is not legalism but pastoral care for covenant integrity.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A type: the whole assembly of Israel gathered at Shiloh to go up to war against them. The mobilization for civil war at Shiloh — the very place from which the eastern tribes just received their blessing — shows how quickly covenant misunderstanding can generate catastrophic conflict. The prevention of civil war through investigation and dialogue (Phinehas&rsquo;s delegation) is the model of church conflict resolution: 1 Corinthians 6:1-6 counsels settling disputes within the community rather than going to war (or to outside courts); Matthew 18:15-17 prescribes the progressive confrontation that Phinehas&rsquo;s embassy enacts here.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A type: the people of Israel sent Phinehas son of Eleazar the priest to the people of Reuben and the people of Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh in the land of Gilead. Phinehas, who turned away YHWH&rsquo;s wrath through his zealous action at Peor (Num 25:7-13), is now sent as the covenant mediator/investigator. The man whose zeal prevented divine wrath is sent as the agent of covenant discernment — the same person who was the avenging priest becomes the reconciling ambassador. Christ who bears the full measure of divine judgment (Col 1:20: &ldquo;making peace by the blood of his cross&rdquo;) is simultaneously the agent of reconciliation sent to those who appeared to be covenant-breakers.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A type: ten chiefs from the tribes of Israel — one per tribe — were sent with Phinehas. The representative-per-tribe structure of the embassy ensures that the confrontation is a covenant-community act, not a unilateral accusation. The ten chiefs represent the entire western covenant community&rsquo;s concern, making their conclusion binding on all Israel. The principle of communal discernment — sending representatives of the whole body — is the church-council principle enacted in Acts 15 at Jerusalem, where representatives of the whole church investigate the Gentile-circumcision question and reach a binding conclusion.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A type: Phinehas and the ten chiefs came to the land of Gilead and spoke to the Reubenites and Gadites and half-tribe of Manasseh and said to them. The direct confrontation — face to face, naming the concern explicitly — is the form of covenant love: &ldquo;you sinned against YHWH&rdquo; is stated directly, not whispered. Matthew 18:15: &ldquo;if your brother sins against you, go and tell him his fault, between you and him alone.&rdquo; Phinehas&rsquo;s embassy is the covenant-community form of this direct confrontation, scaled to a tribal level but following the same principle of loving directness.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A type: the accusation — &ldquo;What is this breach of faith (<em>ma'al</em>) you have committed against the God of Israel?&rdquo; The term <em>ma'al</em> (breach of faith in sacred things) is the technical term for sacrilege that appeared in Achan&rsquo;s sin (Josh 7:1). The western tribes are applying the most serious covenantal charge possible — the same charge that brought disaster at Ai. The seriousness of the accusation reflects the seriousness of covenant integrity: the community cannot afford to treat a <em>ma'al</em> lightly, because YHWH&rsquo;s presence with the whole community depends on covenant purity.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A type: is the iniquity of Peor too little for us, from which we have not cleansed ourselves even to this day, and there came a plague upon the congregation of YHWH? The warning by analogy — Peor caused a plague on all Israel — shows that individual or sub-group sin affects the whole covenant body. The Peor incident (Num 25: sexual immorality with Moabite women) is the paradigm of how sin in one part of the covenant community generates judgment on the whole. First Corinthians 5:6: &ldquo;your boasting is not good. Do you not know that a little leaven leavens the whole lump?&rdquo; — the same logic as the Peor warning: corporate accountability requires corporate vigilance.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A type: and you must turn away today from following YHWH, and tomorrow he will be angry with the whole congregation of Israel. The temporal logic — your act today brings YHWH&rsquo;s anger on all tomorrow — is the covenant solidarity principle at maximum clarity. What any part of the covenant body does affects the whole body&rsquo;s standing before the covenant suzerain. Ephesians 4:15-16: &ldquo;speaking the truth in love, we are to grow up in every way into him who is the head... the whole body, joined and held together by every joint with which it is equipped... makes the body grow&rdquo; — the health of each part affects the whole, as the sin of each part endangers the whole.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A type: if your land is unclean, cross over to the LORD&rsquo;s land where his tabernacle stands and take a possession among us. The invitation to cross over — to physically relocate to the land of YHWH&rsquo;s sanctuary presence rather than remain in separate territory — is the maximum offer of covenant incorporation. Hebrews 10:19-22: &ldquo;we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus... let us draw near with a true heart in full assurance of faith.&rdquo; The geographic crossing-over to the sanctuary that the western tribes offered the eastern tribes is surpassed by Christ&rsquo;s opening of the way into the Most Holy Place — the true crossing-over that abolishes all geographic distance from the divine presence.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A type: did not Achan son of Zerah commit <em>ma'al</em> regarding the devoted things, and wrath fell upon all Israel? The Achan analogy confirms the western tribes&rsquo; logic: one person&rsquo;s sacrilege brought judgment on all Israel, and he did not perish alone in his sin. The corporate liability principle — one sinning causes all to suffer — is the background for understanding Christ&rsquo;s substitutionary atonement: just as Adam&rsquo;s sin brought death to all (Rom 5:12: &ldquo;death spread to all men because all sinned&rdquo;), so Christ&rsquo;s obedience brings life to all who are in him (Rom 5:18-19). The Achan-on-all-Israel type is the negative form of the Adam-on-all-humanity type that Christ reverses.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A type: the eastern tribes&rsquo; defense — invoking the divine triple name as witness: &ldquo;El Elohim YHWH! El Elohim YHWH! He knows, and let Israel itself know.&rdquo; The triple divine-name invocation as solemn oath-formula is the highest possible covenant witness. The accumulation of divine names — El (the mighty one), Elohim (God), YHWH (the covenant name) — invokes the full divine character as witness to the oath&rsquo;s truthfulness. Hebrews 6:13: &ldquo;when God made a promise to Abraham, since he had no one greater by whom to swear, he swore by himself.&rdquo; The divine self-witness in the triple name is the covenant-oath form that anticipates the Father&rsquo;s testimony to the Son (John 5:37: &ldquo;the Father who sent me has himself borne witness about me&rdquo;).</p>",
    "22": "<p>A type: if it was in rebellion or in breach of faith against YHWH — do not spare us today. The eastern tribes submit to the western community&rsquo;s judgment: if we are guilty, execute us. The willingness to accept the full covenant penalty if proven guilty is the form of covenant integrity. Christ&rsquo;s submission to the Father&rsquo;s judgment — &ldquo;not my will, but yours, be done&rdquo; (Luke 22:42) — is the perfect form of this submission. He who was not guilty submitted to the full penalty on behalf of those who were: the ultimate inversion of the eastern tribes&rsquo; conditional submission (they said &ldquo;punish us if guilty&rdquo;; Christ said &ldquo;I will receive the punishment for the guilty&rdquo;).</p>",
    "23": "<p>A type: if we built the altar to turn away from following YHWH — let YHWH himself require it. The self-imprecation with YHWH as the executor of the penalty is the covenant-oath&rsquo;s ultimate form: appealing to YHWH himself as both judge and executioner if they lie. The logic anticipates Hebrews 10:28-31: the severity of covenant judgment under the old covenant was real; how much more severe the judgment for trampling the Son of God underfoot (v29). The eastern tribes&rsquo; self-imprecation with YHWH as judge is the shadow of the &ldquo;it is a fearful thing to fall into the hands of the living God&rdquo; (Heb 10:31).</p>",
    "24": "<p>A type: the explanation — they built the altar because they feared future generations would be told &ldquo;what have you to do with YHWH the God of Israel? YHWH has made the Jordan a boundary between us and you.&rdquo; The fear that geographic separation would become covenantal separation drives the altar&rsquo;s construction. The anxiety about being cut off from the covenant community by a physical boundary is the pastoral heart of the eastern tribes&rsquo; action. Christ&rsquo;s own prayer (John 17:11: &ldquo;Holy Father, keep them in your name that you have given me, that they may be one, even as we are one&rdquo;) addresses the same fear: that the physical separation of death and distance might break the unity of his community.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A type: &ldquo;YHWH has made the Jordan a boundary between us and you, you people of Reuben and Gad; you have no portion in YHWH&rdquo; — the feared future exclusion. The anxiety that the Jordan&rsquo;s boundary would create a theological second-class — people with &ldquo;no portion in YHWH&rdquo; — is the covenant-exclusion fear that the altar addresses. In the NT, the dividing wall between Jew and Gentile created exactly this anxiety (Eph 2:12: Gentiles were &ldquo;alienated from the commonwealth of Israel and strangers to the covenants of promise, having no hope and without God in the world&rdquo;). Christ&rsquo;s reconciling work eliminates the dividing boundary: no Jordan-boundary, no Gentile-exclusion, in the one body.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Therefore we said, &lsquo;Let us now build an altar&rsquo; — not for burnt offering nor for sacrifice, but to be a witness between us and you.&rdquo; The witness-altar is a monument to covenant unity, not a rival place of sacrifice. The distinction between the sacrificial altar (where YHWH&rsquo;s atonement is enacted) and the witness monument (that testifies to covenant belonging) is critical. There is one altar of sacrifice: Christ&rsquo;s cross (Heb 10:10-14: &ldquo;by that will we have been sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all&rdquo;). All subsequent monuments and memorials — including the Lord&rsquo;s Supper — are witness-monuments to the one sacrifice, not supplements to it.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A type: the altar as witness that they perform the service of YHWH before him with burnt offerings and sacrifices — lest future generations say they have no portion. The witness function of the altar is explicitly forward-looking: it is for future generations, not present benefit. The Lord&rsquo;s Supper is the NT counterpart — &ldquo;do this in remembrance of me... until he comes&rdquo; (1 Cor 11:24-26) — a forward-looking witness monument that declares the covenant meal&rsquo;s validity for every future generation until Christ returns. The Jordan altar anticipates the Supper&rsquo;s trans-generational witness function.</p>",
    "28": "<p>A type: &ldquo;if they say this to us in the future, we shall reply &lsquo;Behold the copy of the altar of YHWH which our fathers made.&rsquo;&rdquo; The altar as the physical argument against future exclusion — a copy (<em>tabnit</em>) of the true altar, a witness monument — is the type of every covenant memorial that grounds present identity in past act. Baptism functions similarly in the NT: the water memorial declares the one baptism into Christ&rsquo;s death and resurrection (Rom 6:3-4) as the ground of present covenant identity. The copy-altar points back to the original act; baptism points back to the defining act of death and resurrection.</p>",
    "29": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Far be it from us (<em>chalilah lanu</em>) that we should rebel against YHWH and turn away this day from following YHWH by building an altar for burnt offerings, grain offerings, or sacrifices, other than the altar of YHWH our God that stands before his tabernacle.&rdquo; The eastern tribes&rsquo; strongest possible rejection of any rival sacrifice-altar affirms the one sanctuary principle. There is one altar of atonement: the tabernacle/temple altar, to which all legitimate sacrifice belongs. In the NT, there is one atonement: the cross of Christ. Hebrews 13:10: &ldquo;we have an altar from which those who serve the tent have no right to eat&rdquo; — Christ&rsquo;s sacrifice is the one altar that the entire new covenant community shares.</p>",
    "30": "<p>A type: when Phinehas and the chiefs of the congregation heard the words of the Reubenites and Gadites and Manassites, it was good in their eyes. The resolution — the confrontation leads to understanding, which produces peace — is the form of Matthew 18:15: &ldquo;if he listens to you, you have gained your brother.&rdquo; The process of direct confrontation, full explanation, and public vindication is the covenant community&rsquo;s conflict-resolution mechanism working as YHWH designed it. The near-civil-war ends not with conquest but with comprehension — a more complete victory than military force could achieve.</p>",
    "31": "<p>A type: Phinehas said, &ldquo;Today we know that YHWH is in our midst, because you have not committed this breach of faith against YHWH. Now you have delivered the people of Israel from the hand of YHWH.&rdquo; The priest&rsquo;s declaration — YHWH is in our midst because you acted faithfully — makes covenant integrity the condition of divine presence. The obverse is equally true: covenant faithfulness preserves divine presence, while <em>ma'al</em> drives it away. This principle reaches its fulfillment in Christ&rsquo;s promise: &ldquo;where two or three are gathered in my name, there am I among them&rdquo; (Matt 18:20) — the community&rsquo;s faithful covenant practice becomes the locus of divine presence.</p>",
    "32": "<p>A type: Phinehas and the chiefs returned from the land of Gilead to the land of Canaan and reported to the people of Israel. The resolution&rsquo;s public announcement — the ambassador&rsquo;s return and report — completes the covenant process: confrontation, investigation, resolution, public reporting. The report is the form of 2 Corinthians 5:20 (&ldquo;we are ambassadors for Christ, God making his appeal through us&rdquo;) — the ambassador who goes, investigates, reconciles, and returns with news of peace. Phinehas&rsquo;s embassy is one of the OT&rsquo;s clearest models of the gospel-ambassador role.</p>",
    "33": "<p>A type: the people of Israel were pleased, and blessed God and spoke no more of making war against them, and did not go up to destroy the land. The averted civil war — the near-catastrophe resolved by faithful process — leaves the community at peace. The blessing of God that the community offers after the resolution is the covenantal doxology: praise is the right response to preserved unity. Romans 15:5-6: &ldquo;May the God of endurance and encouragement grant you to live in such harmony with one another... so that together you may with one voice glorify the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ.&rdquo;</p>",
    "34": "<p>A type: the Reubenites and Gadites called the altar Witness (<em>Ed</em>), &ldquo;for it is a witness between us that YHWH is God.&rdquo; The altar named &ldquo;Witness&rdquo; becomes a permanent physical declaration: YHWH is God, and this stone testifies to the covenant unity of the separated communities. Revelation 3:14 names Christ as &ldquo;the faithful and true witness (<em>martus</em>)&rdquo; — the ultimate Witness who testifies that YHWH is God and that his covenant people are one. The Jordan altar&rsquo;s name is a type: the true Ed/Witness between God and his people, between the separated communities of east and west, Jew and Gentile, is Christ himself.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>A type: after a long time — when YHWH had given Israel rest from all their surrounding enemies — Joshua summoned all Israel. The rest-gift that enables Joshua&rsquo;s farewell is the Canaan-rest that Hebrews identifies as the provisional fulfillment pointing to the eschatological rest. Hebrews 4:8: &ldquo;if Joshua had given them rest, God would not have spoken of another day later on.&rdquo; The rest of Canaan (real, historical, comprehensive — YHWH gave it) is not the final rest but the pattern and pledge of it. The &ldquo;long time afterward&rdquo; before Joshua&rsquo;s farewell is the fullness of the land-rest period; the &ldquo;another day&rdquo; of Psalm 95 and Hebrews 4 is the fullness of the Christ-rest that remains.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A type: Joshua summoned all Israel — its elders, leaders, judges, and officers. The full covenant leadership assembly for Joshua&rsquo;s farewell mirrors the full assembly at Sinai and the Shechem renewal (ch. 24). The death-discourse of the covenant leader — the farewell speech that becomes the covenant community&rsquo;s inheritance — is the form of Moses&rsquo;s Deuteronomy farewell and Christ&rsquo;s upper-room discourse (John 13-17). The dying leader&rsquo;s last words are not biography but covenant theology: what Israel needs to know to survive and thrive in the land is what Joshua teaches in his dying speech.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A type: &ldquo;You yourselves have seen all that YHWH your God has done to all these nations for your sake, for it is YHWH your God who has fought for you.&rdquo; Joshua&rsquo;s summary of the conquest as YHWH fighting for Israel is the theological verdict that the military narrative embodies. Romans 8:31: &ldquo;If God is for us, who can be against us?&rdquo; is the NT form of this summary: the rhetorical question assumes the answer of Joshua 23:3 as its premise. Paul&rsquo;s confidence in God&rsquo;s advocacy is grounded in the conquest history — the pattern of YHWH fighting for his people has its ultimate expression in God&rsquo;s not sparing his own Son (Rom 8:32).</p>",
    "4": "<p>A type: Joshua allotted to Israel the remaining nations as an inheritance for the tribes, from the Jordan to the Great Sea in the west. The inheritance of what is not yet possessed — the nations allotted as future inheritance even while some remain unconquered — is the form of the &ldquo;already/not yet&rdquo; eschatological inheritance. Hebrews 11:1: &ldquo;faith is the assurance of things hoped for, the conviction of things not seen.&rdquo; The tribes receive their allotment as inheritance even before full possession — faith takes what the divine grant gives before experiential possession is complete.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A direct revelation (through Joshua): &ldquo;YHWH your God will push them back before you and drive them out of your sight, and you shall possess their land, just as YHWH your God promised you.&rdquo; The future-tense divine promise for the remaining conquest is the same form as Philippians 1:6: &ldquo;he who began a good work in you will bring it to completion at the day of Jesus Christ.&rdquo; Joshua&rsquo;s farewell does not minimize the remaining work but grounds the expectation of completion in the same YHWH who has already accomplished so much. The promise of completing what was begun is the structure of Christian hope.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Therefore be very strong to keep and to do all that is written in the Book of the Law of Moses, turning aside from it neither to the right hand nor to the left.&rdquo; The strength-for-obedience formula (cf. Josh 1:7: &ldquo;be strong and very courageous, being careful to do according to all the law&rdquo;) frames the covenant obligation as requiring active, sustained commitment to the written Torah. Matthew 5:17-18: &ldquo;Do not think that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them... not an iota, not a dot, will pass from the Law until all is accomplished.&rdquo; The total Torah-fidelity Joshua commands is answered in Christ&rsquo;s perfect fulfillment — the completion that Joshua could command but not achieve.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A type: &ldquo;that you may not mix with these nations remaining among you or make mention of the names of their gods or swear by them or serve them or bow down to them.&rdquo; The four-fold prohibition against the remaining nations&rsquo; religious influence — mention, oath, service, worship — covers every level of religious engagement from speech to body. Second Corinthians 6:14: &ldquo;do not be unequally yoked with unbelievers&rdquo; — Paul&rsquo;s application of the separation principle to the church extends Joshua&rsquo;s covenantal warning. The warning against being shaped by the surrounding culture&rsquo;s gods is perennial: every generation of the covenant community faces the same temptation to accommodate the idol-systems of its neighbors.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A type: &ldquo;But you shall cling to YHWH your God just as you have done to this day.&rdquo; The verb <em>dabaq</em> (cling/cleave) is the same word used in Genesis 2:24 (&ldquo;a man shall leave his father and his mother and hold fast to his wife&rdquo;) and Ruth 1:14 (Ruth &ldquo;clung to&rdquo; Naomi). The covenantal clinging is the marriage-fidelity metaphor: total attachment, irreversible loyalty. Romans 8:38-39: &ldquo;neither death nor life... will be able to separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus our Lord&rdquo; — the NT fulfillment is not Israel&rsquo;s clinging to YHWH (which will fail, as the subsequent history shows) but Christ&rsquo;s inseparable love clinging to his own. The dabaq becomes unconditional when Christ does the holding.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A type: YHWH has driven out before you great and strong nations, and no man has been able to stand against you to this day. The invincibility of Israel when YHWH fights for them is the historical testimony that grounds the covenant exhortation. The invincibility principle is not military but covenantal: Israel&rsquo;s strength is entirely derivative of YHWH&rsquo;s fighting-for. In Christ, the same pattern: &ldquo;we are more than conquerors through him who loved us&rdquo; (Rom 8:37) — the conquest is through the one who fights for us, not through our own military or spiritual capability.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A type: &ldquo;One man of you puts to flight a thousand, since it is YHWH your God who fights for you, just as he promised.&rdquo; The arithmetic of divine empowerment — 1,000:1 — is the holy-war ratio that signals divine presence: normal military math is reversed when the divine warrior is the true combatant. Philippians 4:13: &ldquo;I can do all things through him who strengthens me.&rdquo; The one-against-a-thousand effectiveness is not the warrior&rsquo;s skill but the divine presence&rsquo;s empowerment. Paul&rsquo;s &ldquo;all things through him&rdquo; is the NT form of the holy-war ratio: the believer&rsquo;s disproportionate effectiveness comes entirely from the indwelling divine power.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Be very careful, therefore, to love YHWH your God.&rdquo; The command to love YHWH — stated as the single most important exhortation in Joshua&rsquo;s farewell — is the Shema&rsquo;s heart distilled. First John 4:19: &ldquo;we love because he first loved us&rdquo; is the NT answer to Joshua&rsquo;s command: the love that Joshua urgently commands is made possible by the prior love of Christ. The &ldquo;be very careful to love&rdquo; shows that love is not merely a feeling but a disciplined covenant commitment — and the ground of that disciplined love is the prior unconditional love of the one who commands it.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A type: if you turn back and cling to the remnant of these nations remaining among you and make marriages with them — the warning against covenant-mixing. The verb <em>dabaq</em> (&ldquo;cling&rdquo;) appears again but now negatively: the wrong clinging is to the nations instead of to YHWH. The ironic inversion is stark: the command of verse 8 is to cling to YHWH; the warning of verse 12 is against clinging to the nations. Second Corinthians 6:14: &ldquo;do not be unequally yoked with unbelievers.&rdquo; The clinging that belongs to YHWH being redirected to the nations is the fundamental covenant apostasy — and its practical form is intermarriage and social integration with those who serve other gods.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A type: the remaining nations will become &ldquo;a snare and a trap for you, a whip on your sides and thorns in your eyes, until you perish from this good land.&rdquo; The four metaphors of covenant curse from the remaining nations — snare, trap, whip, thorns — are the instruments of the judgment that the subsequent history will enact. First Corinthians 15:33: &ldquo;do not be deceived: bad company corrupts good morals.&rdquo; The same principle — proximity to false worship and practice corrupts covenant integrity — is Paul&rsquo;s application to the Corinthian church. The thorns-in-eyes image echoes the wilderness experience (Num 33:55: &ldquo;those you allow to remain will become barbs in your eyes and thorns in your sides&rdquo;) — the same warning reiterated at the land&rsquo;s reception.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A direct revelation (Joshua&rsquo;s personal testimony): &ldquo;I am about to go the way of all the earth, and you know in your hearts and souls, all of you, that not one word has failed of all the good things that YHWH your God promised concerning you; all have come to pass.&rdquo; This is the OT&rsquo;s most comprehensive single statement of divine promise-faithfulness: not one word failed. Second Corinthians 1:20: &ldquo;For all the promises of God find their Yes in him [Christ].&rdquo; Joshua&rsquo;s territorial testimony (all land-promises fulfilled) is the type; Paul&rsquo;s christological testimony (all covenant promises fulfilled in Christ) is the antitype. The <em>lo nafal davar</em> (not one word fell/failed) of Joshua&rsquo;s dying testimony becomes the Yes and Amen of the gospel.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A type: just as all the good things that YHWH promised have come to pass for you, so YHWH will bring upon you all the evil things until he has destroyed you from off this good land. The double-edged faithfulness of YHWH — the same reliability that guarantees blessings guarantees curses — is Joshua&rsquo;s most sobering teaching. Hebrews 10:28-29: &ldquo;anyone who has set aside the law of Moses dies without mercy on the evidence of two or three witnesses. How much worse punishment, do you think, will be deserved by the one who has trampled underfoot the Son of God?&rdquo; The principle of covenant symmetry — equal reliability of blessing and curse — is intensified in the new covenant: if YHWH&rsquo;s land-curses were real and swift, the new covenant consequences for rejecting Christ are proportionally more severe.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A type: &ldquo;if you transgress the covenant of YHWH your God, which he commanded you, and go and serve other gods and bow down to them. Then the anger of YHWH will be kindled against you, and you shall perish quickly from off the good land that he has given to you.&rdquo; The final covenant warning is simple and direct: the path from idolatry to exile is short. Revelation 20:9: the final gathering of all who have aligned against God ends with fire from heaven consuming them — the eschatological form of the covenant curse Joshua warns about. The temporal land-loss Israel will experience from covenant violation is the historical enactment of a principle that has its ultimate expression in the final judgment, where those who serve other gods are excluded from the new creation.</p>"
  }
}

